snippet.textDisplay: That's true, those tracks are great. But I suppose I'm talking about this particular style of calm. I mean, Earthbound, despite all it's dealings with Aliens and time travel and stuff, still had this feel that it was still taking place in our world, which lead to some pretty awesome jazz-like tracks and overall kept everything sounding kinda modern. You weren't exploring some alien world or anything like that. You were just walking from town to town, haha. Plus, Chiptunes=Yes. For me, anyway.

snippet.textDisplay: Hmm, not sure why so many people say there's no more memorable music in games anymore. I played Assassin's Creed Revelations and it had some amazing pieces in it, big fan of Jesper Kyd (Can't say for ME3 though, ME2 had ok music). I think Extra Credit did a good explaining that since melody was the main focus in older games, it was easier too remember and be hummed. Too me, harmony and atmosphere is just as important as good melody but melody sticks in your head easier. Interesting topic.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is actually why I don't like these ultra realistic graphics. Afterall, we aren't incapable of imagination we use it with books, comics, online fiction etc. And even in older games in still turns on.
Now with the graphics being such high quality, no one bothers to use their imagination because it's right there on the screen for you.
Case in point give most kids these days a visual novel or text based game and they'll almost instantly deem in bad or not interested.

snippet.textDisplay: I had a love/hate relationship with this part of the game.  You had that irritating monkey maze and the fetch quest for Trout Yogurt.  You also had awesome experiences seeing the Runaway Five and Venus, Moonside's trippy atmosphere, and ROB's cameo in the Monotoli Building.  My biggest regret is not getting the game earlier as I was 19 in 2009 when I first played it on my SNES with a $70 price tag for the cartridge alone.
